    <note>Huang(2) Ce(2) [18946] Yuanfu coalition. He was shackled and sent to Dengzhou (probably for transport to Shamen dao) for his opposition to Cai(1) Jing [1649] in 1100, but was allowed to return home as the result of an amnesty. According to Shen(2) Yuqiu [1460], the family was a distinguished lineage (wangzu) of Jianning, Pucheng, which generation after generation produced office-holders. Ce(2)'s grandfather Ting [3419] (q.v.) moved to Wuxian. This lineage was almost certainly a branch of the Pucheng, Jiangxia Huang(2), but there are, as yet, no extant documentary links. Ce(2) is also listed as a Jianning, Ouning jinshi in 1091 in Fujian TZ, 147.34b, which would suggest that the Pucheng Jiangxia Huang(2), the Suzhou Huang(2) and the Ouning Huang(2) all are descended from a common root lineage. ReCHECK funerary inscription. Shen Yuqiu, WJ, 12.7b; Wujun zhi, 26.11a; YLDD, 2367.12a, 2368.4b. CBD, 4, 2858.</note>
